URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS72829575	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			100			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Island (Aleutian Is.)	L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	1980-05-30	08:30:00	13th day of an Attour visit of 2 weeks, with Larry Balch, Thede Tobish, Dan Gibson, Ben King, Guy McCaskie, Terry Moore, Alan Keith, Paul DuMont, Paul Sykes, Jerry Rosenband et al. About 40 birders on island, but the checklist is just what I saw. I spent the morning on a long hike towards Temnac Bay with about half of our tour group, hoping for Gray Bunting from yesterday, but no luck. Then spent a couple hours trying to get views of Siberian Rubythroat, and did. Spent 4 hours scoping from Murder Pt. (2-6 p.m.) with borrowed Questar -- all the alcid counts are from there. I did not keep track of numbers of common resident birds ("x" on checklist) after the first day. Coverage this day was the hike toward Temnac, then Navy Town, then scoping at Murder Pt. Seeing and photographing the cliff-nesting colonies of seabirds was one of the greatest experiences of my life. We were there June 13-17, but I kept a running list rather than daily lists (there would have been much duplication if I had), and so chose the middle date to make this single entry. The seabirds were essentially uncountable, and I was there for the experience more than for making counts, which the guides would be doing anyway. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709561	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-20	19:30:00	After enjoying the stint we hoofed it back to the boat and motored west to Etienne Bay. Thede Tobish had suggested to the team of leaders that we try Etienne as an alternate location to land. Since we had spent nearly a week in the Massacre Bay area we were happy for a change of pace, especially since Etienne was at the far southwestern tip and closer to arriving Asian birdsÂ¿ Ettienne also had the allure of being unexplored by birders, so we were eager to put the place on the birding map. The trip west was fairly uneventful for seabirds, although I thoroughly enjoyed seeing a Parasitic Jaeger chase a Peregrine Falcon, then seeing the tables turn as the Peregrine chased the jaeger, and then seeing it switch again. One highlight as we entered Ettienne was a Whiskered Auklet that Steve Heinl spotted, which is known from just 2 prior Attu records. Ettienne Bay was fascinating in that the composition of seabirds was totally unlike that at Massacre Bay. Least Auklets were common in the mouth (we had none off Massacre). The eiders at Ettienne were mostly males, while in Massacre females predominated. And finally, we had loons: several species of loons. Steve Heinl (again) spotted a breeding plumaged Yellow-billed Loon at a distance but we motored slowly up to it and everyone got good looks. A second first-summer Yellow-billed was seen as well. And later, while the leaders scouted the shore for possible landing sites and birding areas, three Arctic Loons (adult and two juveniles) were spotted as well (I saw these well through the scope with Steve Heinl). When the birds were called into the ship only a few people were able to find these distant loons, but still, the different bird composition held exciting possibilities for the day that followed. L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-15	07:30:00	Our second full day on Attu, this was our first day exploring the Massacre Bay/Coast Guard Station area. One team of 35 checked the Casco Cove and Murder Point area; another team worked Peaceful River, the runways, and the coast guard station, and a third team hiked the Henderson River valley. An additional team of two leader scouts (me and Dave Wolf) checked out Alexai Point, where little seemed to have changed from the previous day and the rare birds were actually scarcer. Their most exciting find was a single Painted Lady (butterfly), which is known from southeast Alaska but has not have occurred in the Aleutians before. Sometime around 9:30 a Tringa sandpiper flew over the Â¿wagtailÂ¿ group giving a mellow, two-noted call. Thede Tobish, who has the most western Alaska experience of any birder on the ship, quickly called the ID | Spotted Redshank!  This was a classic Attu experience, with teams of people assembling on a rare bird and maneuvering to get good views for everyone, although it took many hours to locate and assemble around the bird. Spotted Redshank is a rare migrant in the western Aleutians, primarily in spring where the Attu high count is four. Attu has but one previous fall record, from 26 Sep 2000. It has turned up rarely across the United States, in places like California, Massachusetts, and New Jersey, but is predictably seen only in Alaska. This was what we came here for. The grand Henderson Marsh stomp turned up other goodies as well. Chief among them was Wood Sandpiper, another rare Asian shorebird that was a life bird for most of the group. An eclipse-plumaged Eurasian Wigeon landed in Smew Pond with the redshank at one point, and a good number of Common Snipe (the Eurasian species recently split from WilsonÂ¿s Snipe) were flushed by the various parties.  WEATHER: The weather today was, if anything, too nice. Sunny, temperatures in the upper 50s and low 60s, with very little wind. OTHER FAUNA: LEPS: PAINTED LADY - 1 (photo; first ever for Aleutians!). MAMMALS: Harbor Seal - x; Sea Otter - x; Minke Whale - x.		obs34603	Marshall	Iliff	S3588715	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419985	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709643	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			1			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-16	07:30:00	On our third day the leaders consulted and decided that birds had been coming too easily. In order for our group to fully appreciate the wonders of seeking birds on Attu, we would need to ensure that we had one day without a big chase, one day without a fantastic Siberian vagrant, one slow day. Today was that day. It is a lot of work to find birds of Attu and to have another day where rarities kept falling in our laps would be to miss out on the feeling of hard work that is so rewarding. WEATHER: The weather was nothing short of perfect and many of us birded much of the day in short sleeves. The little bit of wind that picked up was just enough to keep it from being downright hot. Many of us got to explore farther than we had in previous days, with some groups reaching Blue Robin Canyon far to the south and others reaching Gilbert Ridge up to the north. The birds seen actually included some nice finds. New for our 2006 Attu list were Common Loon, Red-necked and Horned grebes, White-winged Scoter, and Pacific Golden-Plover. Repeat rarities included Spotted Redshank and Wood Sandpiper, as well as Gray-tailed Tattler, Eurasian Wigeon, White Wagtail, and Thick-billed Murre. Several people were able to add these species to their life lists today. My group enjoyed a group of passerines hopping about on a rusty cart. All five commonly breeding songbirds (not counting Common Raven) were feeding together on the edge of this cart: Gray-crowned Rosy-Finch, Snow Bunting, Lapland Longspur, Song Sparrow, and a seemingly out-of-place Winter Wren. OTHER FAUNA: MAMMALS: Minke Whale; Harbor Seal; Sea Otter.	near docks	obs34603	Marshall	Iliff	S3588711	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419986	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709808	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			10			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-21	07:30:00	On this morning we continued with our "normal" departure schedule (7:30, 7:50, and 8:10) for our Ettienne Bay landings, but this time just formed groups on the beaches as zodiacs arrived. One group proceeded up the river valley (which ultimately lead to a lake), another started west down the beach, while the last group was going to work the middens, small marsh, and cliff bases nearest the landing site. Our plans were spoiled almost immediately by a radio call from Barry Zimmer. Barry had hoofed it top speed up the river valley with the goal to check the lake to see if anything on the lake could justify the one mile walk. Just 20 minutes after our first landing Barry had found the bird of the trip. His radio call went something like this: "Uh Victor, you better get people up here, I have something REALLY good. It's a small Phylloscopus warbler with wingbars and crown stripes, maybe Eastern Crowned Warbler." In a rush of excitement, well before I had time to actually think about the best course of action, I turned to my group and screamed "RUN! If you can run, RUN! This is a REALLY GOOD BIRD!" Barry didn't have a book, but from his description in later radio calls it sounded like Yellow-browed Warbler. after a long effort, we got diagnostic photos and the persistent all got to see this elusiove mega-rarity. This was only a third record for the Western Hemisphere, with both prior records coming from Gambell, Alaska (23-24 September 1998 and 30 August 2002). Only two people had seen it previously in North America, and it was bird #400 for Dave Sonneborn's Alaska list. It turned out to be the only truly rare passerine that we saw during our week on Attu (Sky Lark and japonicus American Pipit are rare but regular migrants). I am still coming down from the high of seeing such an exciting bird and successful working as a team to show such a furtive bird to a group of 100. L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-20	07:30:00	On this final morning groups split up to look for whatever birds had been missed. Some folks birded the warehouse area for wagtails; others returned to Debris Beach hoping for better looks (if that is possible) at the Sharp-tailed Sandpipers; while another group (including me) checked Smew Pond and Henderson Marsh. The redshank was not present at Henderson for the first time since its discovery, but other groups managed to refind the Black-backed Wagtails, the japonicus American Pipit, and the Sharp-tailed Sandpipers. At least two new birds were found. One was an adult tundrius Peregrine Falcon, a very pale subspecies that nests in the high arctic and is a very rare visitor to the Aleutians. The other was a juvenile Long-billed Dowitcher, another rare migrant on Attu. During lunch the ship repositioned to place us off the tip of Alexai Point. Our scouting party had been covering the point for most of the day, and other than refinding the Baikal Teal and having an interesting peep that flew off before it could be conclusively identified, they were having a slow day. We disembarked and split into two parties: one to go see the three Tufted Ducks and the other to check the runway. The Tufted Duck group was successful and everyone had great looks at the birds on the water. Just as they were finished looking, the scouts called in an exciting report. They had refound the small sandpiper and it was a juvenile Red-necked Stint! Amazingly, it was on the same stretch of beach that had had the Western Sandpiper on our first day. We rushed over there, along with two zodiacs of people who had tried to skip the Alexai Point effort (when they thought Tufted Duck was the best bird on the point). The entire mass of people rushed to the beach where the stint was obligingly foraging in the kelp. The scouts had identified the bird by call and by plumage, but the question of Little Stint was still raised. Since this was a fairly bright Red-necked, the identification was not straightforward, but we all noted this birdÂ¿s dull wing coverts contrasting with the bright scapulars, the fairly indistinct supercilium that was not split, the grayish wash to the sides of the breast, the shorter and slightly decurved bill, and ultimately the call. I used an iPod to elicit a call response from the stint, and it perked up nicely and called back, eliminating any hope for Little Stint.	first-summer, Massacre Bay	obs34603	Marshall	Iliff	S3588709	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	4	8.047		15	1	G419991	1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709751	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-19	07:30:00	Today was our last full day covering the greater Coast Guard station area and our three groups divided up to cover the three major sections. The morning was rather wet, and there were periods of wind and rain that almost recalled the weather that had been predicted for Attu. To be sure, our group was incredibly lucky for the wonderful weather conditions during our time there. The Spotted Redshank was again in position at Smew Pond, and it seemed to have gotten used to our presence and allowed closer approach | a welcome change from its first day when it would flush at almost any distance. There clearly was an arrival of Sharp-tailed Sandpipers overnight, possibly migrant birds that were grounded by the inclement weather. The Smew Pond group had four Sharp-taileds, including at least a couple that literally "dropped from the sky" in front of them. Along Debris Beach we found three Sharp-taileds together at about 9:00 and found the birds to be incredibly approachable. After prolonged scope views at 100 feet we closed the distance to about 20 feet while the birds unconcernedly foraged on the upper part of the beach. As we moved down the beach a fourth Sharp-tailed appeared and joined the other three, and later in the day their number had swollen to seven. Photographers had a field day with these birds, which remained just as confiding throughout the day. Two groups had single Pectoral Sandpipers, and some people got to study both species in the same day, comparing the brighter plumage, mostly unstreaked breasts, and streaked undertails coverts of the Sharpies. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS49709713	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-18	07:30:00	Today got off to an early good start as well. Before most groups had even loaded Larry Balch called from Navy Town asking, "Does anyone want to see a Snowy Owl?" The Spotted Redshank was feeding in its "usual" spot and seemed to have become accustomed to groups of tourists gawking at it. We watched it spend about five minutes trying to swallow an oversized minnow that seemed to be stuck in its gullet. We were worried we might have to administer emergency care, but eventually the fish was swallowed and we can report that our redshank did live to see another day. Another massive rarity chase was set in motion when we glanced through the mist and fog to the back side of Smew Pond where a mid-sized shorebird was foraging. It turned out to be a juvenile Sharp-tailed Sandpiper, an Asian species that we had expected to see before this and which we began to worry that we would miss. Sharp-taileds are uncommon migrants throughout western Alaska, and can even be found predictably in the Pacific Northwest states during September and October, but which is accidental elsewhere in the country. It was a welcome lifer for much of the ship and so groups started converging on Smew Pond. Almost everyone got the bird immediately, but when one of the last groups arrived we had a bit of a scare. The Sharp-tailed flew upriver and was lost from sight for about 20 minutes. We tried to carefully walk the riverbed to flush the bird again and others of us carefully scanned the pond edge in case it had returned to its favored spots. Even when we knew where it was the Sharp-tailed had been very difficult to spot, and continuously moved in and out of the grasses at the edge. Perhaps it was not surprising then that the bird was missed. I had been the appointed riverwalker, and when I reached the pond I decided to try playing its call since it had earlier shown some level of tape response. As soon as I keyed up the iPod a shorebird started flying directly for me from the far side of the pond. It turned out to be the Sharp-tailed and on its return visit it gave great looks to the worried recent arrivals and lifted a great burden from the leaders' shoulders. We spent a long time absorbing its key field marks, which sunk in especially well for those of us that had carefully studied similar Pectoral Sandpipers in previous days. Several groups undertook ambitious afternoon walks. My group headed up Henderson Valley to Bird Canyon and Lake Elwood. Lake Elwood produced another new bird for the trip: an American Wigeon. This was perhaps the only time that I had seen Eurasian Wigeon (2) outnumber American (1), and it was one of the better comparative studies I have had. The gray head of the American contrasted markedly with its breast (little to no contrast on Eurasian). Almost on command, the American rose out of the water and flapped, revealing its diagnostic white underwing. Our other neat find on that long walk was a second Snowy Owl, this one a pure white adult sitting high on the rocky cliffs of Terrible Mountain. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844591	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			10			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-21	07:30:00	On this morning we continued with our "normal" departure schedule (7:30, 7:50, and 8:10) for our Ettienne Bay landings, but this time just formed groups on the beaches as zodiacs arrived. One group proceeded up the river valley (which ultimately lead to a lake), another started west down the beach, while the last group was going to work the middens, small marsh, and cliff bases nearest the landing site. Our plans were spoiled almost immediately by a radio call from Barry Zimmer. Barry had hoofed it top speed up the river valley with the goal to check the lake to see if anything on the lake could justify the one mile walk. Just 20 minutes after our first landing Barry had found the bird of the trip. His radio call went something like this: "Uh Victor, you better get people up here, I have something REALLY good. It's a small Phylloscopus warbler with wingbars and crown stripes, maybe Eastern Crowned Warbler." In a rush of excitement, well before I had time to actually think about the best course of action, I turned to my group and screamed "RUN! If you can run, RUN! This is a REALLY GOOD BIRD!" Barry didn't have a book, but from his description in later radio calls it sounded like Yellow-browed Warbler. after a long effort, we got diagnostic photos and the persistent all got to see this elusiove mega-rarity. This was only a third record for the Western Hemisphere, with both prior records coming from Gambell, Alaska (23-24 September 1998 and 30 August 2002). Only two people had seen it previously in North America, and it was bird #400 for Dave Sonneborn's Alaska list. It turned out to be the only truly rare passerine that we saw during our week on Attu (Sky Lark and japonicus American Pipit are rare but regular migrants). I am still coming down from the high of seeing such an exciting bird and successful working as a team to show such a furtive bird to a group of 100. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844455	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-19	07:30:00	Today was our last full day covering the greater Coast Guard station area and our three groups divided up to cover the three major sections. The morning was rather wet, and there were periods of wind and rain that almost recalled the weather that had been predicted for Attu. To be sure, our group was incredibly lucky for the wonderful weather conditions during our time there. The Spotted Redshank was again in position at Smew Pond, and it seemed to have gotten used to our presence and allowed closer approach | a welcome change from its first day when it would flush at almost any distance. There clearly was an arrival of Sharp-tailed Sandpipers overnight, possibly migrant birds that were grounded by the inclement weather. The Smew Pond group had four Sharp-taileds, including at least a couple that literally "dropped from the sky" in front of them. Along Debris Beach we found three Sharp-taileds together at about 9:00 and found the birds to be incredibly approachable. After prolonged scope views at 100 feet we closed the distance to about 20 feet while the birds unconcernedly foraged on the upper part of the beach. As we moved down the beach a fourth Sharp-tailed appeared and joined the other three, and later in the day their number had swollen to seven. Photographers had a field day with these birds, which remained just as confiding throughout the day. Two groups had single Pectoral Sandpipers, and some people got to study both species in the same day, comparing the brighter plumage, mostly unstreaked breasts, and streaked undertails coverts of the Sharpies. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844280	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			1			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-16	07:30:00	On our third day the leaders consulted and decided that birds had been coming too easily. In order for our group to fully appreciate the wonders of seeking birds on Attu, we would need to ensure that we had one day without a big chase, one day without a fantastic Siberian vagrant, one slow day. Today was that day. It is a lot of work to find birds of Attu and to have another day where rarities kept falling in our laps would be to miss out on the feeling of hard work that is so rewarding. WEATHER: The weather was nothing short of perfect and many of us birded much of the day in short sleeves. The little bit of wind that picked up was just enough to keep it from being downright hot. Many of us got to explore farther than we had in previous days, with some groups reaching Blue Robin Canyon far to the south and others reaching Gilbert Ridge up to the north. The birds seen actually included some nice finds. New for our 2006 Attu list were Common Loon, Red-necked and Horned grebes, White-winged Scoter, and Pacific Golden-Plover. Repeat rarities included Spotted Redshank and Wood Sandpiper, as well as Gray-tailed Tattler, Eurasian Wigeon, White Wagtail, and Thick-billed Murre. Several people were able to add these species to their life lists today. My group enjoyed a group of passerines hopping about on a rusty cart. All five commonly breeding songbirds (not counting Common Raven) were feeding together on the edge of this cart: Gray-crowned Rosy-Finch, Snow Bunting, Lapland Longspur, Song Sparrow, and a seemingly out-of-place Winter Wren. L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-15	07:30:00	Our second full day on Attu, this was our first day exploring the Massacre Bay/Coast Guard Station area. One team of 35 checked the Casco Cove and Murder Point area; another team worked Peaceful River, the runways, and the coast guard station, and a third team hiked the Henderson River valley. An additional team of two leader scouts (me and Dave Wolf) checked out Alexai Point, where little seemed to have changed from the previous day and the rare birds were actually scarcer. Their most exciting find was a single Painted Lady (butterfly), which is known from southeast Alaska but has not have occurred in the Aleutians before. Sometime around 9:30 a Tringa sandpiper flew over the Â¿wagtailÂ¿ group giving a mellow, two-noted call. Thede Tobish, who has the most western Alaska experience of any birder on the ship, quickly called the ID | Spotted Redshank!  This was a classic Attu experience, with teams of people assembling on a rare bird and maneuvering to get good views for everyone, although it took many hours to locate and assemble around the bird. Spotted Redshank is a rare migrant in the western Aleutians, primarily in spring where the Attu high count is four. Attu has but one previous fall record, from 26 Sep 2000. It has turned up rarely across the United States, in places like California, Massachusetts, and New Jersey, but is predictably seen only in Alaska. This was what we came here for. The grand Henderson Marsh stomp turned up other goodies as well. Chief among them was Wood Sandpiper, another rare Asian shorebird that was a life bird for most of the group. An eclipse-plumaged Eurasian Wigeon landed in Smew Pond with the redshank at one point, and a good number of Common Snipe (the Eurasian species recently split from WilsonÂ¿s Snipe) were flushed by the various parties.  WEATHER: The weather today was, if anything, too nice. Sunny, temperatures in the upper 50s and low 60s, with very little wind. OTHER FAUNA: LEPS: PAINTED LADY - 1 (photo; first ever for Aleutians!). MAMMALS: Harbor Seal - x; Sea Otter - x; Minke Whale - x.		obs162787	Steven	Heinl	S10875062	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		15	1	G419985	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844394	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Massacre Bay	L498123	H	52.8472601	173.2157707	2006-09-18	07:30:00	Today got off to an early good start as well. Before most groups had even loaded Larry Balch called from Navy Town asking, "Does anyone want to see a Snowy Owl?" The Spotted Redshank was feeding in its "usual" spot and seemed to have become accustomed to groups of tourists gawking at it. We watched it spend about five minutes trying to swallow an oversized minnow that seemed to be stuck in its gullet. We were worried we might have to administer emergency care, but eventually the fish was swallowed and we can report that our redshank did live to see another day. Another massive rarity chase was set in motion when we glanced through the mist and fog to the back side of Smew Pond where a mid-sized shorebird was foraging. It turned out to be a juvenile Sharp-tailed Sandpiper, an Asian species that we had expected to see before this and which we began to worry that we would miss. Sharp-taileds are uncommon migrants throughout western Alaska, and can even be found predictably in the Pacific Northwest states during September and October, but which is accidental elsewhere in the country. It was a welcome lifer for much of the ship and so groups started converging on Smew Pond. Almost everyone got the bird immediately, but when one of the last groups arrived we had a bit of a scare. The Sharp-tailed flew upriver and was lost from sight for about 20 minutes. We tried to carefully walk the riverbed to flush the bird again and others of us carefully scanned the pond edge in case it had returned to its favored spots. Even when we knew where it was the Sharp-tailed had been very difficult to spot, and continuously moved in and out of the grasses at the edge. Perhaps it was not surprising then that the bird was missed. I had been the appointed riverwalker, and when I reached the pond I decided to try playing its call since it had earlier shown some level of tape response. As soon as I keyed up the iPod a shorebird started flying directly for me from the far side of the pond. It turned out to be the Sharp-tailed and on its return visit it gave great looks to the worried recent arrivals and lifted a great burden from the leaders' shoulders. We spent a long time absorbing its key field marks, which sunk in especially well for those of us that had carefully studied similar Pectoral Sandpipers in previous days. Several groups undertook ambitious afternoon walks. My group headed up Henderson Valley to Bird Canyon and Lake Elwood. Lake Elwood produced another new bird for the trip: an American Wigeon. This was perhaps the only time that I had seen Eurasian Wigeon (2) outnumber American (1), and it was one of the better comparative studies I have had. The gray head of the American contrasted markedly with its breast (little to no contrast on Eurasian). Almost on command, the American rose out of the water and flapped, revealing its diagnostic white underwing. Our other neat find on that long walk was a second Snowy Owl, this one a pure white adult sitting high on the rocky cliffs of Terrible Mountain. L418947	H	52.908902	173.0044556	2006-09-20	07:30:00	On this final morning groups split up to look for whatever birds had been missed. Some folks birded the warehouse area for wagtails; others returned to Debris Beach hoping for better looks (if that is possible) at the Sharp-tailed Sandpipers; while another group (including me) checked Smew Pond and Henderson Marsh. The redshank was not present at Henderson for the first time since its discovery, but other groups managed to refind the Black-backed Wagtails, the japonicus American Pipit, and the Sharp-tailed Sandpipers. At least two new birds were found. One was an adult tundrius Peregrine Falcon, a very pale subspecies that nests in the high arctic and is a very rare visitor to the Aleutians. The other was a juvenile Long-billed Dowitcher, another rare migrant on Attu. During lunch the ship repositioned to place us off the tip of Alexai Point. Our scouting party had been covering the point for most of the day, and other than refinding the Baikal Teal and having an interesting peep that flew off before it could be conclusively identified, they were having a slow day. We disembarked and split into two parties: one to go see the three Tufted Ducks and the other to check the runway. The Tufted Duck group was successful and everyone had great looks at the birds on the water. Just as they were finished looking, the scouts called in an exciting report. They had refound the small sandpiper and it was a juvenile Red-necked Stint! Amazingly, it was on the same stretch of beach that had had the Western Sandpiper on our first day. We rushed over there, along with two zodiacs of people who had tried to skip the Alexai Point effort (when they thought Tufted Duck was the best bird on the point). The entire mass of people rushed to the beach where the stint was obligingly foraging in the kelp. The scouts had identified the bird by call and by plumage, but the question of Little Stint was still raised. Since this was a fairly bright Red-necked, the identification was not straightforward, but we all noted this birdÂ¿s dull wing coverts contrasting with the bright scapulars, the fairly indistinct supercilium that was not split, the grayish wash to the sides of the breast, the shorter and slightly decurved bill, and ultimately the call. I used an iPod to elicit a call response from the stint, and it perked up nicely and called back, eliminating any hope for Little Stint.	first-summer, Massacre Bay	obs162787	Steven	Heinl	S10875077	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	4	8.047		15	1	G419991	1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS154844535	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			X			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Aleutians West	US-AK-016	US-AK_1009	Attu Is.--Ettienne Bay	L498125	H	52.9220479	172.6477432	2006-09-20	19:30:00	After enjoying the stint we hoofed it back to the boat and motored west to Etienne Bay. Thede Tobish had suggested to the team of leaders that we try Etienne as an alternate location to land. Since we had spent nearly a week in the Massacre Bay area we were happy for a change of pace, especially since Etienne was at the far southwestern tip and closer to arriving Asian birdsÂ¿ Ettienne also had the allure of being unexplored by birders, so we were eager to put the place on the birding map. The trip west was fairly uneventful for seabirds, although I thoroughly enjoyed seeing a Parasitic Jaeger chase a Peregrine Falcon, then seeing the tables turn as the Peregrine chased the jaeger, and then seeing it switch again. One highlight as we entered Ettienne was a Whiskered Auklet that Steve Heinl spotted, which is known from just 2 prior Attu records. Ettienne Bay was fascinating in that the composition of seabirds was totally unlike that at Massacre Bay. Least Auklets were common in the mouth (we had none off Massacre). The eiders at Ettienne were mostly males, while in Massacre females predominated. And finally, we had loons: several species of loons. Steve Heinl (again) spotted a breeding plumaged Yellow-billed Loon at a distance but we motored slowly up to it and everyone got good looks. A second first-summer Yellow-billed was seen as well. And later, while the leaders scouted the shore for possible landing sites and birding areas, three Arctic Loons (adult and two juveniles) were spotted as well (I saw these well through the scope with Steve Heinl). When the birds were called into the ship only a few people were able to find these distant loons, but still, the different bird composition held exciting possibilities for the day that followed. The tour included a lunch stop at Fox Island where a few new birds were seen.  The large seabird nesting colonies seen along the way were spectacular and most varied at Cape Resurrection where Common Murre, Pigeon Guillemot, Black-legged Kittiwake, Horned and Tufted Puffins, and Red-faced Cormorant breed. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS127636287	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			3			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Kenai Peninsula	US-AK-122	US-AK_1089	Kachemak Bay (SW of Homer Spit)	L588693	H	59.5962308	-151.5014648	2011-10-08	09:00:00			obs174299	Dan	Crowson	S8919132	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD_AK	240	8.047		3	1		1	0		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS127615994	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			3			United States	US	Alaska	US-AK	Kenai Peninsula	US-AK-122		Kachemak Bay	L653941	P	59.5677233	-151.5893555	2011-10-08	09:00:00	This is a field trip report for this falls Kachemak Bay Campus birding class.  This 4 hour boat trip started at the Homer Harbor, headed north along the Homer Spit to Mud Bay, then over to Gull Island, a bit into China Poot Bay, then Sixty-foot Rock, Cohen Island, Yukon Island, around Hesketh Island, and then back to the harbor.  In addition to seeing 28 species of birds we also saw 5 species of mammals; many sea otters, 5 river otters on Yukon Island, 1 harbor seal and 1 Steller's sea lion near Gull Island and a pod of about 10 humpback whales feeding and breeching in the outer part of Kachemak Bay.  Unusual bird sightings include 2 Pacific Wrens on Gull Island and a small flock of about 3 Fox Sparrows on Sixty-foot Rock.  The waterbird sightings were spread throughout the Bay, as you might expect.  Many species, particularly the murres and loons, seemed to be in molt.----Weather was very good for this time of the year.  It was in the upper 30s at the start of the trip and then warmed to the 40s.  Seas were calm and skies were mostly clear.		obs51101	George	Matz	S8917788	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD_AK	240	32.187		7	1		1	0

Weather was perfect with very small swells at about 13 seconds apart meaning NOBODY got sick on the trip.	One adult first spotted by Daryl Coldren. L109049	H	38.046914	-123.463217	2006-09-24	07:00:00	Fogged out the entire day which meant that any birds seen were seen well. Debi's trip report: http://www.shearwaterjourneys.com/cb060924.htm----Shearwater Journeys' pelagic trip from Bodega Bay on Sunday, September 24, 2006 was just about socked in with fog all day long. The seas were very calm, and winds were very light. We went about 29 miles offshore. Nevertheless, highlights included SIX SPECIES OF ALCIDS: XANTUS' MURRELET (1) spotted by Alan Hopkins, sitting on the water, giving excellent views to the entire boat load of birders; TUFTED PUFFIN (1), also sitting on the water on the Cordell Bank on the 50 fathom line; CASSIN'S AUKLET (6), some allowing great views (this species has largely been absent this year due to the lack of krill); RHINOCEROS AUKLET (145); PIGEON GUILLEMOT (8), mostly in the harbor area; COMMON MURRE (250), many chicks still with their dads. Other highlights included a great show in the jaeger department, some nice photo-ops of SABINE'S GULLS sitting on the water; one BLUE-WINGED TEAL about 19 miles offshore; 1 or 2 WILSON'S STORM-PETRELS only 12 miles offshore, feeding; a good show on the BULLER'S SHEARWATERS; and two FRIENDLY HUMPBACK WHALES who checked out our vessel! Whale snot! ----Finally, I want to say that we saw some of the most tremendous schools of ANCHOVIES breaking the surface of the flat-calm seas. These were some of the largest schools of anchovies that I have ever seen, covering huge areas of the ocean. BLUE SHARKS were also very evident. The presence of these two fish in such numbers indicates to me that there is a huge plankton bloom, and maybe, just maybe we will see some krill. If so, we could see some Blue Whales, and more murrelets.		obs103121	Matt	Brady	S11040265	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	480	48.28		25	1	G432281	1	0

L351269	H	36.7158249	-122.0627976	1971-10-03	08:15:00	This was my first Mty Bay pelagic, and I kept a complete list. My list does not have numbers, though; to the extent available, these were retrieved from Am Birds Vol. 26, No. 1, pp 112-115. The trip was led by Bill Reese & Alan Baldridge. It is mistakenly attributed to "Oct 4" in AmBirds, but Oct 4 was a Monday in 1971. My notes are correct: Oct 3, a Sunday. This type of mistake is rampant in old issues of AmBirds. The storm-petrel numbers, single Fork-tailed St-Petrel & TUPU, and the few Xantus''s Murrelets are reported in the published issue. L351269	H	36.7158249	-122.0627976	1996-12-01	07:30:00	My first pelagic trip.  Shearwaters Journeys Trip.  7:30 AM to 2:30 AM.  Cost $69.  Birded with Corinne Garlock. L607172	H	36.6025196	-122.5014496	2010-09-25	19:15:00	Shearwater Journeys boat trip organized by American Bird Conservancy., Debra Shearwater leading the trip. Boat went 20 miles into the ocean. Moderate sea state, sunny, excellent visibilty. Gulls were attracted by chum and hung off stern the entire trip and were joined by albatrosses. Jaegers were attracted to the boat toward tail end of voyage.  Sooty shearwaters, Cassin''s Auklets,and phalaropes were in particularly large groups. Western Gull attacked a puffin and forced it to submerge. ----We also saw hundreds of California Sea Lions and some sea otters close to shore, a Northern Fur Seal well out to sea, 200 Northern Right Whale dolphins, 150 Risso''s Dolphins, some Pacific White-sided Dolphins, 20 Humpback Whales and a Fin Whale. Two Blue Whales were feeding on the surface and dived under the boat. Abundance of krill drew large numbers of whales.    		obs113347	Louis	Warren	S6930823	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	480	64.372		15	1		1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS128319899	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			1			United States	US	California	US-CA	Monterey	US-CA-053		Monterey Bay pelagic (MTY Co.)	L351269	H	36.7158249	-122.0627976	2011-10-15	08:30:00	On board the Point Sur Clipper with Mty Seabirds leaders Roger Wolfe, Dan Singer, Todd Easterla, Fritz Steurer, Tim Amaral, Bruce Elliot, etc (leaders/hands equaled numbers of regular customers it seemed.) Weather foggy at first leaving the breakwater but yielding rather quickly to a fresh southeasterly and intermittent sun and high clouds. Beaufort 4+ relaxing at 2-3 early in the afternoon. Planned route took us south from Point Pinos to the Sur Ridge and hard water temperature break, but weather conditions and adverse seas forced us to turn east and northward somewhere off Point Lobos. Subsequently we wandered northward to pass the SCz county line, but only briefly, and then zigzagged around to near inshore off moss landing before returning to moor. Considerable avian activity throughout the day with no quiet stretches. Highlights included 4 Flesh-footed Shearwaters, Tufted Puffin, app. 6 fly-by Xantus Murrelets, Short-tailed Shearwater. Also noteworthy were many sizable migrant duck flocks including many far offshore, largely Pintail and Shovelers. This was my first pelagic this year with much of the winter gull compliment in evidence through the chum line. Mammal highlights sparse, but good experiences had with big, diffuse Risso's Dolphin pods, bow-riding Dall's Porpoise, and a first fall migrant Gray Whale; probably a bull or errant non-breeder.		obs168285	Jim	Moore	S8969789	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	300	32.187		15	1	G304647	1	0

L329116	H	37.69852	-123.002789	1977-06-19	06:00:00	I spent 18-25 June 1977 living on SEFI. Virtually all of the vagrants were netted & banded [I have many in-hand photos] and most stayed for days (and one point I watched 1 TEWA, 2 Cape May, 1 Blackb, 1 CSWA, 1 AMRE at same time, hopping among elephant seals in ''garbage gulch,'' one of the few spots out of the wind); the Black-throated Sparrow was a male seen daily. I spent hours in murre, puffin, cormorant, and oystercatcher blinds, doing counts & recording behaviors. I had the estimates of total population numbers for that time for the island, and have extrapolated those to list what I personally saw (e.g., most of the 23000 WEGUs, cormorants, but rather small numbers of the storm-petrels and CAAU [only 500 of 110000 population]. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS162115784	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			4			United States	US	California	US-CA	San Francisco	US-CA-075	US-CA_143	Southeast Farallon Island (SF Co.)	L329116	H	37.69852	-123.002789	2012-06-24	10:30:00	Our trip out to the Farallon Islands on the "Outer Horizon" with Captain Jim Robertson was highlighted by our time around the islands in search of the Northern Gannet, and although it took some time to locate, we did eventually see this bird.  This list began as we approached the northern islands and then continued around these islands and just off their northwestern end, where we spent some time looking at some breaching Humpback Whales.  We then made the short trip south to Southeast Farallon Island, where we spent an extended period of time (12:10-1:00 pm) along the eastern shore searching carefully for the gannet.  It took some effort and probably quite a bit of luck, but we did manage to see the gannet sitting among a large colony of nesting Common Murres on the slope above Fertilizer Flat.  As a result of the time we spent checking the northern islands, the waters between the northern islands and the main island, and the northeastern shore of the main island, we did not have time to continue around to the west side of Southeast Farallon Island (though I doubt anybody was disappointed).  Most of the murres were seen on the islands themselves, but we also saw many in the water off the north end of the southern island.  Although I was not surprised by how few puffins we saw, I would have expected we would have seen more auklets than we did.  Given how calm the waters were, my main regret was not bringing a scope, with which I suspect I could have obtained exceptional views of the gannet.  Also on the boat were Larry Sansone, Dan Maxwell, Jon Dunn, Paul Lehman, Guy McCaskie, Todd McGrath, Brian Daniels, Dave Pereksta, Barbara Carlson, Matt Brady, Wes Fritz, Vernon and Andrew Howe, Dave Quady, and about 20 others.  It was clear, with at most a mild (5 knot) breeze from the west, air temperatures in the upper 50s to low 60s, and a west or northwest swell that was no more than 3-4 feet at its peak.  10:30 am - 1:00 pm.----Gray Whale - 1 (I missed this one as we approached SE Farallon Island);--Humpback Whale - 4-5 (we saw two just east of the northern islands and two or three others to the northwest of these islands; both sets of whales were breaching actively);----The photo below of a breaching Humpback Whale was taken by Todd McGrath a short distance off the northwest end of the northern island----<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/35719772@N06/7484234796/" title="_MG_9769 by toddamcgrath, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8001/7484234796_365c85c7c8.jpg" alt="_MG_9769"></a>----Steller's Sea-Lion - 1-2 (calling; we saw at least one large male on the island, where Matt Brady also heard this same individual or another);--California Sea-Lion - 20 (I was told that most of the sea-lions that we saw on the island represented this species). L329116	H	37.69852	-123.002789	2012-06-30	11:00:00	nearshore circumnavigation of the island at 100 m offshore, aboard  "Outer Limits"  with Captain Jim Robertson (SF Bay Whale Watch), with naturalist Carol Keiper; John Luther, Jim Lomax, Suzanne Methnin, Bruce Barrett, J.T. Lewis, Scott & Linda Terrill, Sandy Koonce, + 20 other birders (and 15 non-birders). Seas flat calm, both enroute and return and during the island visit, but fog drifting in and out, so some bright sun, some dense fog, some in-between. It took nearly 3 hours to get here (with a whale stop) and a bit more to return to S.F. (more whale stops; all Humpbacks enroute). We did have a small Gray Whale at N tip of SE Farallon I. This was a search for N. Gannet trip for the 30 birders, and much effort in primary area called "Fertilizer Flats," but all the 'big white birds' onshore were gulls. [It was seen on similar trip last Sunday]. Lewis, Scott & Linda Terrill, Sandy Koonce, + 20 other birders (and 15 non-birders). L977081	H	37.6448477	-123.0684013	2012-08-18	09:00:00	aboard a SF Whale Watch trip on "Kitty Kat" catamaran, with skipper Joe, naturalists Reese and Renata, and 40 other non-birders. I was hoping for the Gannet. We circumnavigated southeast Farallon and covered the half-mile or so offshore in that circuit, but the viewing was very badly hampered by low fog over the island (no gannet). Seas a bit rough (Bft 4) from NW winds in a.m., then to Beaufort 5 (~16 knots) in p.m., but boat very stable and comfortable. Cold & overcast much of time, with spray; some sun mid-day but very foggy at Farallones and to the west. As a whale-watch trip, we had a Humpback east of island, and then another Humpback 6 mi to W, over the continental shelf. This whale was doing a lot of full breaches -- very impressive -- but for the fog, which ruined the photo efforts. This checklist excludes the 2 nmi miles around SE Farallon (and excludes the hour spent there). L329116	H	37.69852	-123.002789	2012-09-12	11:38:00	The primary focus of today's trip with Alvaro's Adventures was the Northern Gannet that had been seen around Southeast Farallon Island since April, and which I had previously seen here on 24 June.  Upon arriving in the vicinity of the island from Pillar Point Harbor, we spent an extended period of time doing loops around Southeast Farallon Island.  During this period, we did our best to scan from distances as near as 100 meters or so the rocks and cliff faces for whatever birds and marine mammals we could find on the island.  Although this was a reasonable distance to look for boobies, gulls, and other seabirds, it was a bit far to identify small land-birds.  We also checked the waters around the island for whatever we could find, with the highlights being large numbers of Cassin's Auklets and a handful of puffins.  The gannet had been relatively predictable on most days, but this was less true today given that we had to circle the island for almost four hours before the call came in over the radio that this bird was approaching.  In addition to Alvaro Jaramillo, the roughly 30 others on the boat included spotters John Sterling and Dan Singer, and participants Don Roberson, John Luther, Jim Lomax, Bruce Barrett, Steve and Pricilla Summers, Richard Norton, Steve and Becky Turley, and Robbie Fischer.  It was fully overcast, with at most a trace (&lt;5 knot) breeze from the northwest, temperatures in the low 60s, and a swell that was 4-5 feet when we arrived before dropping to 2-3 feet over the course of our visit.  11:38 am - 4:15 pm.--I have included in brackets the official numbers for the trip shared by Alvaro.  In some cases I have used his numbers, but in most cases, and especially when there was a major discrepancy between the two sets of numbers, I stuck with the numbers in my written notes.----passerine sp. - 1 (a small passerine seen on the island may have been a Black Phoebe);--Gray Whale - 2;--California Sea-Lion - 400;--Steller's Sea-Lion - 20;--Northern Elephant Seal - 15;--Northern Fur Seal - 10-15. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS163593313	4625	species	Tufted Puffin	Fratercula cirrhata			3			United States	US	California	US-CA	San Francisco	US-CA-075	US-CA_143	Southeast Farallon Island (SF Co.)	L329116	H	37.69852	-123.002789	2012-09-12	11:45:00	aboard 'New Captain Pete' (53' fishing boat) with skipper Dennis Baxtor, Eric deckhand, with Al Jaramillo, Dan Singer, John Sterling as leaders; with John Luther, Suzanne Methnin, Jim Lomax, Curtis Marantz, Roy Carlson, Peter LaTourrette, R.L. Norton, Gary Deghi, Alan Hopkins, Steve & Priscilla Summers, Liz West, David Nelson, Robbie Fischer, et al. (37 paying passengers, including me), for 'gannet chase trip' to SE Farallon I.  Overcast & cool, and some lengthy swells, but seas remarkably calm throughout trip, down to Beaufort 1 by end of day. Let Pillar Pt. Harbor 8:30 a.m., arrived SEFI at 11:45, and circumnavigated the island 3-4 times over the course of the next 4 hours [I think it is about a 2 mi circumnavigation, so I put 6 mi for distance spent here). Much waiting and watching at various spots, but mostly just W of island, until 3:31 p.m. when we reached a radio call from Farallones biologist that the gannet had returned and was circling Lighthouse hill!  Much excitement as we watched it for a half-hour, first in flight and then landing about a third of the way up the hill, and then preening and resting (distant photos). Returned to Pillar Pt. Harbor about 7 pm, after enjoying fine view of a Leatherback sea-turtle about 14 miles NW of the harbor. Also 2 Gray Whale seen often at Farallones, plus Cal & Steller's Sea-lions, N. Fur Seal, N. Elephant Seals (15), Harbor Seals. Smattering of molas enroute, plus a Humpback (in SM, I think) and many Chrysarea jellies where the turtle was found. This checklist is for the island and the waters immediately off the island only. I anticipate the 'shared checklist' will eventually appear, and may adjust my estimates.		obs107968	Don	Roberson	S11574451	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	255	9.656		40	1		1	0

L596932	H	37.0157122	-122.6953125	1990-09-09	07:00:00	a 12-hr trip from Monterey harbor aboard 'Pt Sur Clipper' with R. Ternullo, skipper; with Debi Shearwater and me as leaders; w/Parker Backstrom et al. We left Monterey 4:30 a.m., went NW and were 8 nmi off Davenport SCZ at dawn. Only common birds there (and no checklist made for SCZ) but reach a point 15 nmi off Ano Nuevo and were within SM waters to a point 25 nmi WSW Ano Nuevo, and 41 nmi WNW of Pt. Pinos, where we entered MTY waters (see separate checklist) and went basically SE to Pt. Pins, where we found 3 Humpback whales right off the Point. All checklists are offshore waters only. My notes do divide species between MTY & SM; the rarer ones specifically by totals, and for more common species I do a reasonable allocation. L769024	H	38.2349441	-123.5110474	2009-09-18	07:10:00	Larry Sansone and I joined a Shearwater Journeys trip led by Debi Shearwater, Todd McGrath, Wes Fritz, Oscar Johnson, Lisa Hug, and Abe Borker.  Also present were Jim Lomax and quite a few others whose names I did not know.  We left port and passed by Bodega Head on a course to the west towards Bodega Canyon, from which we continued southwest to a depth of 1300 fathoms before turning back to the east and passing by Cordell Bank on our way back towards the port.  We again saw many jaegers and quite a few albatrosses, but few shearwaters and nothing particularly rare, with the best bird being an adult Tufted Puffin.  It was clear but somewhat hazy all day, with a mild (10-15 knot) breeze, apparently from the northwest, and temperatures probably ranging from the low 50s to the low 60s.  Water temperatures ranged from about 55-61Â° F, with the higher temperatures well offshore.  The seas were quite manageable with a northwest swell of about 8 feet in the morning dropping to 3-5 feet late in the day.  Given limited wind, there also was little in the way of wind waves and no white caps.  7:10 am Â– 6:20 pm.----Bracketed numbers are the official numbers for the trip taken from the notes of Oscar Johnson.  Oscar did not include in his lists the birds seen around the harbor, but he tallied his numbers in three separate lists, one for the nearshore waters in Sonoma County (7:35-8:15 am; 5.5 mi.), another for the offshore waters in Sonoma County (8:15-11:55 am; 30 mi.), and a third for Marin County (11:55 am Â– 6:00 pm; 40 mi.).  Although Oscar appears to have included more than half of the day in his list for Marin County, my understanding was that we were in Marin County waters for only a brief period shortly after noon before returning to Sonoma County for most of our return to port.  My impression was that OscarÂ’s numbers for the common gulls and both Common Murres and CassinÂ’s Auklets were quite low, but those for the remaining species were comparable to my estimates.----Blue Whale - 2 [3];--Humpback Whale - 10;--California Sea Lion - 10;--Northern Fur Seal - 1 (I missed this one);--Harbor Seal - ?? (not sure how many were seen because I did not see them);--Mola Mola - 1;--Salmon Shark - 1.	An adult seen in Marin County had an extensively white face that contrasted with a black crown, nape, upperparts, and wings.  I never really saw much of the underparts, but what I did see appeared to be black.  The bill was conspicuously deep, rounded distally, and a bright orangey-red in color.  There seemed to be some clouding in the face and I think the golden tufts were somewhat reduced.  The feet appeared to be pale yellow, at least when seen through the water.	obs54638	Curtis	Marantz	S5350815	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	670	120.698		35	1		1	1

Observers were Bill Tweit, Charlie Wright, Scott Horton, Liam Antrim, Beth Phillips, Tiffanie.  The usual survey route, heading NW from Bouy Q off LaPush from 0920 to 1200, then straight north along the shelf edge from 1200 to 1300, back SE from the outermost point to Sea Lion Rocks, and finally south along the coast back to Buoy Q.   Sea and weather conditions were generally very good, with light winds.  Skies were mostly overcast, some shower activity generated local, light squalls.  Swells about 1 to 1.5 meters, primarily from the west with light wind waves on top.   Cetaceans included 3 Humpback Whales, a couple of small schools of Dall's Porpoise, Harbor Porpoise near shore, and one school (25+) of Pacific White-sided Dolphins.  Pinnipeds included several Steller's Sea Lions at sea, numerous Steller's on Sea Lion Rocks, one California Sea Lion near shore, and one Harbor Seal nearshore.  Also had several Sea Otters, one on the rocks just outside of the LaPush Harbor, and one several miles offshore, a couple in the usual nearshore zone. The usual survey route, heading NW from Bouy Q off LaPush from 0920 to 1200, then straight north along the shelf edge from 1200 to 1300, back SE from the outermost point to Sea Lion Rocks, and finally south along the coast back to Buoy Q.   Sea and weather conditions were generally very good, with light winds.  Skies were mostly overcast, some shower activity generated local, light squalls.  Swells about 1 to 1.5 meters, primarily from the west with light wind waves on top.   Cetaceans included 3 Humpback Whales, a couple of small schools of Dall's Porpoise, Harbor Porpoise near shore, and one school (25+) of Pacific White-sided Dolphins.  Pinnipeds included several Steller's Sea Lions at sea, numerous Steller's on Sea Lion Rocks, one California Sea Lion near shore, and one Harbor Seal nearshore. Most comments and some additional data are augmented from Peter Carr's Birder's Diary records, Bob Schmidt's photos, and collective memory.  Regarding the distance covered for this checklist, Westport Seabirds has been using the following protocol for the last two years (2010, 2011): data is recorded on 3 checklists; 1 for Harbor to 3 miles out, 3 miles out to Chum and back, then again at 3 miles out to dock.  This 2007 checklist is not as carefully segregated and includes some birds, mainly Larus sp. Gulls and Black-legged Kittiwake from the Westport jetty and perhaps even Marina).  Therefore we arbitrarily call the distance covered for this checklist 1 miles out to Chum and back.  Bob Schmidt has many pictures of additional species from within Wesport Harbor and other nearshore waters which are recorded on a second 'Westport -- Marina' HotSpot checklist, with a distance covered set as 1 mile.  While there is some overlap in the areas of the Westport Jetty and surrounding waters, we believe that the combined counts are conservative and perhaps have even missed some species.  Thus the 'Westport -- Marina' HotSpot checklist is marked as incomplete.
